segments.text: I believe we've already mentioned a little bit about the athletes having the privilege of the training table.
Were there any other assets to being an athlete?
Well, I can't say, Charles, that I didn't letter to A&M.
I lettered on the freshman team, but we played with the varsity in baseball and basketball, and we didn't get a letter as such.
And I was a pitcher, and I never did get a letter on the varsity.
But I stayed on the squad a great deal of the time.
I don't think I can be classified as an athlete.
I tried.
But since you were on the squad, you were eligible for the training table for the whole time.
That's right.
But you still had to do all your drills and wear your uniform and regulation.
I presume that if there was a drill scheduled while you were supposed to be practicing, you would be excused from the drill.
That's right.
In checking through the yearbook during your senior year, I had an indication there that you were president of something called the NTAC Club.
That's the North Texas Cultural College.
That was Grubbs, that's the old Grubbs Vocational College that I entered in 1916 to get in the uniform.
My family sent me up there so I wouldn't go into the army.
I had a brother in service and they didn't want two of us in service and I was settled to go at 16 anyway.
But that's what that was, North Texas Agricultural College.
And it's now University of Texas in Arlington, as you well know.
So this would be an organization of all the boys who had been through that particular school prior to coming to A&M.
That is correct.
Okay.
You were also on the staff of the Fish Battalion in 1920.
I know there was a time period of years where they had a magazine for each class and some special events.
Was this that particular issue?
That was that particular issue.
We had the opportunity, the freshman class had the privilege of publishing the battalion one time.
And that's when I was on the editorial staff.
In fact, I still have that battalion.
It's quite something.
We have most of those that were in magazine format.
Yes, that's what that was.
I think you were also a member of an organization called One-Buttoneers.
I was, and that was the brave second lieutenants.
And we, I don't know whether it's through sheer embarrassment by being a second lieutenant or just because we wanted to have some fun, so we organized.
And we had several dances, the one known as the One-Button Ears.
And we just had a great time as second lieutenants on the campus.
And I don't know whether all the boys belonged to the One-Button Ears or not, but anyway, it was a fun thing.
So that was kind of a social organization.
It was, and as I mentioned, we had some dances.
So this would be a contribution to the social life of the campus.
That's right.
And were the dances just for the members of the club or not open to the rest of them?
That's right.
And you were also in the RVs.
Was that for one year or for two?
I was in the RVs two years, two years, because I couldn't have been voted in my first year because I was a freshman.
And I was in the RVs my junior and senior year.
You said you were voted in.
Yes.
Was that still where somebody recommended you?
That's right.
And everybody voted?
I understand it was a no blackball thing.
If you were one blackball, you didn't get in.
It was a military and social organization.
Uh-huh.
Did that require a fair amount more drill practice?
We did drill quite a bit, and we thoroughly enjoyed it.
We had the white uniforms they have today, quite a bit of gold braid.
I'm sure you've seen those pictures.
Did you participate in any special drills or special exhibitions?
No, we didn't, except on the campus.
didn't go off campus as the way the RVs do today.
No, not, I believe they go to New Orleans.
They go to New Orleans, I think they were at the opening of the Constitutional Convention.
That's right, and they also are at the governor's inauguration.
That's right, we didn't do that.
Okay, and when you graduated in the spring of 24, did you have a job lined up
Before graduation, or did you have to hunt one?
No, in 1924, during that period, for three or four or five years, there were many opportunities.
Our economic conditions were good, and I think most anyone who graduated from college or university could get jobs.
And I had two or three or four job offers.
And I did go with Ralston Purina, which I haven't regretted.
and was with Ralston Purina 42 years and thoroughly enjoyed it and I had a fair degree of success.
I believe you began as a salesman in St. Louis.
That's right.
That's where we trained and I came to Texas to do some extra training.
and was given a territory or a district in the Rio Grande Valley of Texas, which was at that time just beginning, just developing.
Now, as a salesman for Ross and Purina, you didn't sell to individuals, did you?
You would sell to distributors?
Well, we sold to distributors, but we also called on ranchers and large feeders.
That was part of our training program, and the salesmen still do that.
So actually you sold both to individuals and to dealers.
That's right.
Distributors.
That's right.
You had each salesman would have a specified territory to cover.
That's right.
That's right.
And then ultimately you became what manager?
Well, I became sales manager.
I was in the Red Grande Valley 15 years as salesman.
District salesman had 27 dealers there.
And
came out here, we came to Lubbock in 1940 as sales manager for this West Texas, part of New Mexico and part of Oklahoma area.
And then in 1945, I went into our plant, which is in Lubbock, as manager of that plant, and stayed until I retired in 1966 as plant manager.
And this is the production of the... Of the chows, our...
the feed.
Is that, how does the plant here in Lubbock say compared to other plants across the arena for production?
We have some plants that are larger but this is one of the very fine plants in the United States and one of the profitable plants on the basis of quite a volume.
It's
You have a lot of livestock in the community to consume.
Yes, we do.
We surely have.
Commodities, as opposed to perhaps more than, say, St. Louis, the headquarters?
It's the headquarters and the home office.
Ralston Pure Rain is about 78 years old.
It was established about 78 years ago.
It's one of the largest feed plants in the world.
It is the largest.
And we're doing business all over the world in many other parts of the business.
We're in the tuna fish business, chicken of the sea tuna.
That's the largest.
We are the largest in the tuna fish business in the world.
That's a subsidiary of Ralston?
A subsidiary of Ralston Purina.
We have several subsidiaries.
We have a serial subsidiary.
And Purina Dog Chows.
We have 11 plants in the United States.
Any plants abroad?
We do.
We have plants in Europe, and we have plants in South America, and we have plants in Mexico.
I visited some plants in South America last summer, in Peru, and also in Brazil.
I believe you said you were with Ralston for 42 years.
Yes.
So you retired then in 1966.
And what have you been doing since then?
I'm a director in the Lubbock Savings and Loan Association.
A group of us organized that association in 1952.
And I was a director then, and I continue to be a director, and have a desk in one of the branches.
I guess my responsibility, Charles, would be public relations, which I enjoy.
And I thoroughly enjoy having been associated with that organization since 52.
I really appreciate it.
And I have a feeling of responsibility.
We all need that.
Now, I believe a little bit ago you indicated that you had jotted down some notes, some things that you wanted to sort of make sure we covered.
Well, not necessarily, Charles.
I just wanted to be sure.
If you were going to run short of time, I was just going to hand this to you, and I didn't know you were going to tape this conversation.
I didn't know how it was going to be, but I just happened to, I did that after I learned that you weren't going to be here.
Did you have some things on there that we haven't covered here?
Uh...
Well, I think we've covered almost everything except what I've done, if that be of any interest, as a citizen of Lubbock.
That would be of interest, yes.
It would be of interest.
Well, there's one thing that I'm real proud of that I didn't mention.
When I was in Rio Grande Valley, I was awarded the William Sample Award, which is an outstanding salesmanship award, and I believe there's only been 125 given
In our period of time that William H. Sample was sales manager of our company, national sales manager of our company.
And we had, through the period of time, we've had about 5,000 salesmen.
And I am very proud of that.
And my district in the Rio Grande Valley was considered the finest district in Ralston Peel Rain Company.
That might sound a little egotistical.
But there are a lot of districts in the United States.
There are a lot of districts in the United States.
We cover the entire country.
And that was from 1925 to 1940.
And then I went into, I became sales manager.
Those are some of the things I've done in Lubbock.
Would you like to have some of those?
civic activities.
In 1953 I was elected President of the Lubbock Chamber of Commerce and I thoroughly enjoyed that.
It was at the time when Lubbock was really beginning to grow and I appreciated being a part of that.
And in 1956 was elected

director of the Lubbock County Water and Improvement District which is known as Buffalo Lakes it was a million eight hundred thousand dollar project and it was a countywide election and I was chairman of that chairman of the board of that the of that district and
In 1956, I resigned from the Lubbock County Water and Improvement District to run for a place on the City Commission, which I did, was elected in 1956 to the City Council.
Served one term.
And in 1952, we organized Lubbock Savings and Loan Association.
I had mentioned that a minute or two ago, and we're still going.
And I did serve as chairman of the Red Cross Financial Drive in Lubbock County and the chairman of the National Foundation of Incentive Paralysis for Lubbock County.
That was before the Salk vaccine was developed.
And we had sent many boys and girls to Shrine and Cripple Children's Hospital in Scottish Rite.
And I was nominated to the
Honorary State Farmer of the FFA at a state meeting in Lubbock about four years ago, and Senator Charles Verner, president of this bank, and I were on that committee, and we were honored in that way.
And I was president of the West Texas Museum Association when it was elected in October 1960.
And that has gotten to be one of the real fine museums in the country.
And that is where?
In Lubbock.
In Lubbock.
Yeah.
It's on the Tech campus.
Now, the West Texas Museum Association?
That's what it's called.
It's known as the West Texas Museum Association.
Is that connected with the ranch headquarters?
That's part of it.
The ranch headquarters is part of it.
And the Tech Museum is not?
And the Tech Museum, that's all the same.
Uh-huh.
OK.
